Written evidence from [bold]the British Association of [bold]Dermatologist[bold]s [bold](LTC 89)[bold]The British Association of Dermatologists is a charity whose objects are the practice, teaching, training and research of Dermatology.
[normal] 
[normal]It is funded by the activities of its Members.
[normal] 
[normal]'Healthy Skin for All' is its motto.
[normal]Many skin[bold] diseases themselves represent LTC[bold]s[bold].[bold]P[bold]eople with [bold]LTCs [bold]in other organs or sy[bold]s[bold]tems commonly get skin disease[bold].[bold] [bold]S[bold]ome skin [bold]LTC[bold]s are associated with increased physical and psychological disease[bold].[bold]The available dermatological[bold] resource is already [bold]seriously[bold] overstretched[bold].[bold]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Chronic skin 
[normal]conditions affect both 
[normal]the 
[normal]young and old and 
[normal]may 
[normal]p
[normal]ersist 
[normal]over the course of a lifetime.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The burden of chronic skin diseases such as leg ulcers and repeated episodes of skin cancer is increasing as the population ages.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Skin disorders are amongst the most common long-term conditions in the UK: there are more than 2,000 different diseases.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There is a large number of genetic skin diseases; each one may only affect a small number of people, but taken together they form part of the long term skin disease burden in the UK.
[normal] 
[normal]For sufferers they are a life sentence of misery, physical and cosmetic disability and psychological challenges.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Skin diseases repres
[normal]ent 34% of disease in children;
[normal] 20% of children in the UK have eczema,
[normal]children with serious skin conditions 
[normal]have their quality of life 
[normal]impaired to the same extent as those with chronic illnesses such as epilepsy, renal disease and diabetes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Acne is an extremely common skin disease 
[normal]-
[normal] 
[normal]often 
[normal]trivialised
[normal] 
[normal]as a 
[normal]‘
[normal]passing phase
[normal]’
[normal] of adolescence
[normal] 
[normal]-
[normal] 
[normal]yet it commonly persists into the 20s and even 30s and 40s in many people (
[normal]up to 5% of all women
[normal]).
[normal] 
[normal]Acne scarring is permanent. Acne results in long term disabilities including difficulties in relationships and employment prospects.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Hand eczema is one of the most common reasons for disablement benefit in the UK
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]3% of the population ha
[normal]s
[normal] psoriasis (with a third suffering since childhood).
[normal] 
[normal]30% of psoriasis patients needing systemic treatmen
[normal]ts have been attending D
[normal]ermatology 
[normal]clinics for over 10 years.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Some lifelong diseases such as vitiligo
[normal],
[normal] which results in the loss of normal skin colour
[normal],
[normal] can have a devastating effect on self-esteem for people from b
[normal]l
[normal]ack and ethnic minorities.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It is estimated that several million people 
[normal]in the UK 
[normal]have significant chronic sun damage 
[normal]resulting in 
[normal]~13,000 melanomas and ~800,000 basal cell and squamous cell skin cancers a year.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]People with chronic sun damage 
[normal]suffer increasing numbers of skin cancers as they age 
[normal]–
[normal] 
[normal]the 
[normal]ageing population will have a bigger incidence of this disease.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]C
[normal]hronic skin disease
[normal] can influence ‘major l
[normal]ife
[normal] changing d
[normal]ecisions
[normal]’
[normal], 
[normal]which then 
[normal]impact on the rest of 
[normal]a 
[normal]person’s life.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In the UK, data from the WHO Global Burden of Diseases study shows that DALYs (Disability Life-Adjusted Years) for skin conditions are as high as those for diabetes, chronic renal disease, gastrointestinal disorders or neonatal abnormalities. The reason is largely because skin disease is 
[normal]so 
[normal]common.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]P
[normal]atients with chronic disease 
[normal]can be 
[normal]affected by skin disease directly
[normal] 
[normal]due to 
[normal]the 
[normal]effects of 
[normal]those diseases
[normal] (
[normal]eg
[normal] diabetes and HIV)
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]P
[normal]eople with other LTCs 
[normal]also 
[normal]get skin problems due to their treatments
[normal]. This is
[normal] 
[normal]especially
[normal] common when treatment includes
[normal] drugs
[normal] such as anti-epileptics
[normal],
[normal] cancer therapies and radiotherapy, or 
[normal]transplants 
[normal]- due to the
[normal] drugs given to prevent transplant rejection
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Increasingly in an ageing population people are 
[normal]on multiple medications: 
[normal]dermatological side-effects 
[normal]are extremely common
[normal],
[normal] ranging from chronic itch
[normal]ing
[normal] and rash
[normal]es,
[normal] to life threatening 
[normal]condition
[normal]s
[normal] warranting 
[normal]hospitalisation
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]P
[normal]atients with chronic psoriasis have increased obesity, hypertension, 
[normal]h
[normal]y
[normal]percholestolaemia
[normal], diabetes, heart disease
[normal] (the metabolic syndrome) 
[normal]and mortality
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]20
[normal]% of patients with psoriasis develop chronic arthritis. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In the United Kingdom, in excess of 10,400 diagnoses of depression, 7,100 diagnoses of anxiety, and 350 diagnoses of 
[normal]suicidality
[normal] are attributable to psoriasis annually
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]24% of the population consults a GP each year because of a skin complaint. Skin disease is one of the 
[normal]most 
[normal]common reason
[normal]s
[normal] for a new consultation with GPs
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]GPs refer approximately 6.1% of these cases to secondary care and in 2010/11 873,000 such referrals were made in England with 2.9m total outpatient appointments for skin diseases.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]T
[normal]here is a 20% under-provision of Dermatology services
[normal] 
[normal]in the UK: 
[normal]with 
[normal]only 650 Consultants
[normal] 
[normal]in the country
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Despite the above statistics, GPs receive on average no more than six days training in Dermatology during the whole of their time as undergraduate and post-graduate medical students, and only around one in five GP training schemes offer a Dermatology element
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]It is therefore inevitable that many doctors will enter General Practice with limited knowledge and understanding of common skin diseases
[normal] 
[normal]that can
[normal] often
[normal] present significant clinical diagnostic and management problems.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Referrals to Dermatology services have risen as a consequence of increasing population numbers
[normal],
[normal] frequency of 
[normal]skin 
[normal]diseases
[normal],
[normal] improved treatments and changing attitudes to skin conditions.
[normal] 
[normal]This is despite the increased number of community based services following the recommendations of the White Paper 
[normal]‘Our health, our care, our say: a new direction for community services’ (2006).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.[bold]              [bold]V[bold]arying the current mix of service [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]2.1
[normal]              
[normal]In the BAD’s document 
[normal]‘Guidance for Commissioning 
[normal]Dermatology
[normal] Services’
[normal] we set out the range and scope of services which would best serve 
[normal]Dermatology
[normal] patients at different levels
[normal],
[normal] including Community Pharmacists and Specialist Nurse
[normal]-
[normal]led clinics supporting patients with self-management, 
[normal]and covering 
[normal]primary and intermediate care to secondary and tertiary services. The BAD supports the provision of a 
[normal]comprehensive 
[normal]mix of services but not the promotion of one type of service over another – there will always be a need for 
[normal]centralised
[normal] 
[normal]hospital
[normal]-
[normal]based services
[normal]. T
[normal]hese continue to be the most cost-effective and safe means of providing direct access to care for patients who are acutely unwell and have complex care needs.
[normal] Increased
[normal] Consultant
[normal]-
[normal]led community services and
[normal] education of primary care doctors and nurses will all help to improve 
[normal]integrated
[normal] care of patients
[normal] through a pyramid of appropriate expertise
[normal],
[normal] so that patients see the right person at the right time
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.[bold]              [bold]The readiness of local NHS[bold] services [bold]to treat patients with [bold]LTCs[bold] (including multiple conditions) within the community[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2
[normal]              
[normal]Clinical Assessment and Treatment 
[normal]Centres
[normal] 
[normal]are also used in some areas to triage and/or review GP referrals to reduce the number of patients 
[normal]referred to
[normal] secondary care.
[normal] 
[normal]The BAD recommends that GP referrals are always triaged by a 
[normal]C
[normal]onsultant 
[normal]Dermatologist
[normal] with 
[normal]GPwSI
[normal] and 
[normal]Dermatology
[normal] nurse support
[normal],
[normal] and that referral management services should only be set up after consultation with all stakeholders, including
[normal] the public and 
[normal]those in secondary care
[normal]. 
[normal]W
[normal]ithout engagement at all levels, referral management services may introduce an additional tier 
[normal]to accessing 
[normal]care, reduce patient choice and quality of care
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]and
[normal] worse still, 
[normal]destabilise
[normal] 
[normal]local NHS hospital
[normal] services
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3
[normal]              
[normal]Providing 
[normal]Care Closer to Home
[normal] often
[normal] 
[normal]involves decommissioning part
[normal]s
[normal] of 
[normal]Dermatology
[normal] Outpatients service
[normal]s
[normal] in order to provide intermediate levels of care in the community.
[normal] 
[normal]However, the objective 
[normal]of such 
[normal]decommissioning – to bring about improvements in service provision 
[normal]- 
[normal]has not been 
[normal]realised
[normal].
[normal] Instead
[normal], there are 
[normal]increased
[normal] referrals to both community and 
[normal]hospital 
[normal]services, rather than reduced referrals to the 
[normal]hospital 
[normal]setting.
[normal] 
[normal]U
[normal]nder the existing 
[normal]Any Qualified Provider
[normal] model, and with the use of private providers,
[normal] 
[normal]recognised
[normal] 
[normal]care pathways across 
[normal]different
[normal] levels of care can become fragmented
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]his happen
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]even when these services are provided by local clinicians under a 
[normal]Limited Liability Partnership
[normal]. In the majority of cases where this has happened the cost of care remains the same per head of patients as the hospital service.
[normal] 
[normal]This cost does not, though, factor in the additional costs for patient care for those 
[normal]‘
[normal]lost
[normal]’
[normal] on the referral 
[normal]pathway 
[normal]between their GP and the community, before getting to secondary care.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.4
[normal]              
[normal]Although moving care closer to home has been a policy ambition for some time, referral rates to both community and secondary care services have continued to rise since its inception, and there are worrying signs that primary care is buckling under the current pressures of demand
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.[bold]              [bold]P[bold]ractical assistance offered to [bold]Commissioner[bold]s [bold]&#xa0;
