[normal]5[bold].[bold]              [bold]The ability of NHS to treat multi-morbidities and the patient as a person [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1
[normal]              
[normal]P
[normal]atients with skin disease often require treatment for existing co-morbidities 
[normal](for example psoriasis and 
[normal]the 
[normal]metabolic syndrome) 
[normal]by 
[normal]their
[normal] GP and 
[normal]Dermatology
[normal] 
[normal]and other specialists
[normal];
[normal] these patients need to be identified 
[normal]bec
[normal]a
[normal]u
[normal]s
[normal]e
[normal] they impact on services across the levels of care and 
[normal]a
[normal]cross specialties.
[normal] A 
[normal]Needs Assessment
[normal] is therefore a crucial step in drawing up service specifications.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2
[normal]              
[normal]Dermatologist
[normal]s are frequently required 
[normal]to review patients under 
[normal]other 
[normal]specialist 
[normal]departments where treatments
[normal],
[normal] both pharmacological and otherwise
[normal],
[normal] can cause side-effects present
[normal]ing
[normal] 
[normal]as skin problems 
[normal]– often causing extra distres
[normal]s, physical morbid
[normal]ity and risk 
[normal]to an already sick individual.
[normal] 
[normal]Drug reactions in skin are a common reason for admission to hospital and sometimes can be life-threatening.
[normal] 
[normal]Immunosuppression
[normal] (for example in HIV, AIDS or following organ transplants) as well as treatments for other cancers and diseases have all led to an increase in the number of people developing skin complications, including secondary skin cancers. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.3
[normal]              
[normal]Identifying
[normal] these 
[normal]dermatological
[normal] co-morbi
[normal]dit
[normal]ies
[normal] 
[normal](
[normal]and their treatment
[normal])
[normal] 
[normal]from coded information is
[normal] particularly problematic 
[normal]as
[normal] 
[normal]the patient 
[normal]under
[normal] 
[normal]care 
[normal]will be 
[normal]logged under 
[normal]another specialty 
[normal]or 
[normal]consultant
[normal]. 
[normal]The
[normal] majority of Trusts have 
[normal]divisional budgets
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal](
[normal]entitled, 
[normal]for example, 
[normal]General Medicine, Medical Specialties
[normal],
[normal] or hosted by another specialist department 
[normal]e.g.
[normal] 
[normal]Plastic Surgery
[normal])
[normal], 
[normal]t
[normal]his
[normal] 
[normal]fails to 
[normal]recognise
[normal] the work of the 
[normal]Dermatology
[normal] 
[normal]D
[normal]epartment 
[normal]because it 
[normal]does not allow 
[normal]a) 
