[normal]6.[bold]              [bold]The implications of an ageing population [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]6.1
[normal]              
[normal]Growth of the ageing population will increase the prevalence of skin 
[normal]LTCs
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Th
[normal]is is highlighted by th
[normal]e DALY statistic
[normal] – although this
[normal] captures disability over the entire population, i
[normal].
[normal]e
[normal].
[normal] young and old, and over time
[normal], o
[normal]ne of the reasons why diabetes is 
[normal]less disabling is that it has 
[normal]higher mortality
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]whilst those with skin conditions continue to live with them into old age
[normal],
[normal] increasing the 
[normal]DALY 
[normal]numbers
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.2
[normal]              
[normal]The skin cancer epidemic gathers pace. The vast majority of skin cancer is due to chronic photo
[normal]-
[normal]damag
[normal]e
[normal] as a result of increased recreational exposure 
[normal]and this
[normal] shows 
[normal]no signs of diminishing
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Many patients will have several episodes
[normal] of skin cancer
[normal] 
[normal]and pre-cancer 
[normal]as they get older. There are about 
[normal]~
[normal]1
[normal]3
[normal],000 melanomas and 
[normal]~8
[normal]00,000 other skin cancers a year in the UK.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.
[normal]3
[normal]              
[normal]With increasing population growth and increasing longevity it is important to invest in 
[normal]Dermatology
[normal] services
[normal], and training in 
[normal]Dermatology
[normal],
[normal] so that the burden of chronic skin disease can be better managed with better outcomes for all patients
[normal]. This
[normal] includ
[normal]es
[normal] the elderly
[normal] a
[normal]nd those whos
[normal]e
[normal] skin disease is due to an associated 
[normal]LTC
[normal] and/or its treatment
[normal].
