[normal]8.[bold]              [bold]Conclusions[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Skin
[normal] disease contributes hugely to LTCs in the UK; 
[normal]m
[normal]illions of people have dermatological LTCs
[normal] such as
[normal] 
[normal]e
[normal]czema, psoriasis, acne
[normal], 
[normal]vitiligo
[normal] and
[normal] occupational skin disease.
[normal] 
[normal]Additionally, 
[normal]there is a 
[normal]grow
[normal]ing sector of the ageing population with chronic
[normal] sun-damage
[normal] and the serial skin cancers that ensue
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Many 
[normal]other primarily non-dermatologica
[normal]l LTCs create significant dermatological needs, 
[normal]due to the disease itself or to its treatment with drugs and their consequences and side effects
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Some dermatological LTCs, especially psoriasis, are associated with significant co-morbidity – the metabolic syndrome
[normal] and arthritis
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]P
[normal]rovision of 
[normal]the 
[normal]type of care 
[normal]affected people 
[normal]need 
[normal]is under
[normal]-
[normal]resourced, 
[normal]fragmented 
[normal]and of variable quality, i
[normal]n terms of manpower and 
[normal]facilities
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]This is
[normal] exacerbated by poor teaching and training 
[normal]of D
[normal]ermatology 
[normal]in Medical Schools and General 
[normal]P
[normal]ractice
[normal],
[normal] and under-
[normal]funding of 
[normal]relevant 
[normal]research. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Addressing these issues of resource, training and research should lead to 
[normal]greatly 
[normal]improve
[normal]d
[normal] care 
[normal]for
[normal] people with LTC
[normal]s 
[normal]delivered by Consultant-
[normal]led
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]vertically integrated 
[normal]service
[normal]s
[normal].
